results.notes: Abundant flushes here today at Flora Vista in Olympia, WA, USA on their favorite host substrate Alnus rubra. Note the pink tinged margin of young fruiting bodies and overall gray tones throughout. Best harvested when young with incurved margins as a rule of thumb(as with all Pleurotus spp.). I like to fry them battered with egg and rolled in a mix of pulverized saltine crackers and panko. A simple/delicious aoli of Srirach and mayonnaise with garlic powder and a dash cumin is perfect for the light, seafood flavor of P. pulmonarius(and other oysters). Planning a young stinging nettle and oyster forage foray here(and at my other favorite spots in coming weeks).
results.location_name: Flora Vista City Park Olympia, Thurston Co., Washington, USA

The first and last photo shows the same specimen as https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/19931507—on 10/11/2018 when it was fresh. So the specimens are almost 7 months old at the time of the more recent photos on this obs.

Of the 3 varnished Ganoderma known to occur in AZ on hardwoods G. curtisii is ruled out here due to the lack of melanoid bands in the flesh. G. polychromum appears to be rare having been documented here once on willow and it has thin varnish that wears off in age. This looks to me to be either G. sessile or G. lucidum sensu stricto since it occurred on a tree that was introduced from Europe. Both share the buff flesh with concentric growth zones that this obs has. Interestingly G. lucidum almost always has a stem and it long relative to the cap diameter while G. sessile rarely has a stem and when it does it is short and thin. I think this may be G. lucidum. We will try to sequence this.

results.notes: Growing on small pieces of woody debris among sandy soil in a floodplain. Caps hygrophanous. results.notes:
Two fruit bodies found on the east side of the trail in a wash. They were growing beneath a log on the south-facing slope of the wash. There was a stream ~20 feet away. 59 degrees out, sunny, around noon. Elevation ~8,800 feet. Other foragers in my area claim that this species is picky about elevation. Despite three hours of hiking on/off trail and crossing similar/identical habitats, and going up to ~9,200 feet and down to ~8,000, I could never find another one. I did observe someone else searching the fringes of a meadow around ~9,000 feet with ponderosa pine, aspen, gambel oak, and white fir trees. It’s either very early season, or this area is atypical or on the edge of its preferred distribution. Someone I spoke with claimed that the Ski basin is their lower limit. This same species grows as low as ~7,000 feet in nearby mountains, and would ostensibly grow lower if that environment could support the trees that it associates with. Unfortunately the forest service has diligently removed most of the Abies concolor from Hyde Park, surely limiting the population of the M. snyderi that can successfully live there. I have yet to ever find a specimen of M. snyderi in New Mexico that wasn’t in some type of vicinity of Abies concolor. I believe this is its preferred mycorrhizal partner. Another consistency is that they seem to behave slightly differently depending on what other trees are around. When I find these in an area with Abies Concolor and Pinus Ponderosa, the fruit bodies tend to cluster 2-4 together. When I find these with Abies Concolor and gambel oak, they seem to come up singly and more spread out, rarely in clusters. They also like to fruit right by rocks, or the stems of small shrubby plants, or other objects in the environment, maybe because the rocks are absorbing more heat and warming the soil there, or creating some type of other micro climate, retaining moisture, etc.

Of course they break all these rules from time to time, but this is what I’ve noticed about M. snyderi. If you’re going to find one, there’s a high probability of Abies concolor being nearby.

notes_fields.Macroscopic_Features: The beetle carcass measures 1.4 cm long by .5 cm wide. The fungus is growing out of the carcass along the edges of the elytra (hard outer wing covering), from the legs, and out of the head, with a larger, seemingly more well defined protrusion from the intersection fo the thorax and abdomen. The fungus is white and whispy.
notes_fields.Microscopic_Features: Conidiophores are visible under the dissection microscope at 20-40x magnification. Conidiophores are awl-shaped and bear ellipsoid conidia singularly on their tapered end. The conidiophores are arranged spirally around a projecting hypha.
